// GALLERY IV — Networks & Empires (1880–1945)  [+ two late–Gallery III entries]
window.ATLAS_EVENTS.push(
{ id:"sepoymutiny", year:1857, date:"1857–1858", era:3, cat:"power",
  title:"The Indian Rebellion of 1857",
  wiki:"Indian Rebellion of 1857", gallery:["British Raj","East India Company"],
  summary:"India rises against East India Company rule; the suppression ends company government and begins the British Raj.",
  importance:"Sepoy grievances ignited a rebellion that took Britain eighteen brutal months to suppress. Parliament abolished the East India Company — the first nationalization of a corporation grown into a state — and assumed direct Crown rule. Colonial surveillance and labor-control practices hardened across the empire, while Indian nationalism began its long organization: the Indian National Congress (1885), the first factory acts (1881), the first unions (1890s), and finally independence (1947).",
  impact:{
    government:"The Company-state is dissolved; formal empire replaces corporate empire.",
    power:"The founding precedent for ending a corporation that had outgrown its charter.",
    labor:"Colonial labor regulation begins — the Indian Factories Act (1881) extends the factory-acts model to the Raj, weakly.",
    society:"Anti-colonial nationalism acquires its martyrs and its memory." },
  causes:["eastindia"], effects:["indianindependence"] },

{ id:"waldeckrousseau", year:1884, date:"1884", era:3, cat:"law",
  title:"France Legalizes Unions",
  wiki:"Waldeck-Rousseau laws", gallery:["Confédération Générale du Travail","Third Republic"],
  summary:"The Waldeck-Rousseau law erases the Loi Le Chapelier after 93 years — French workers may finally organize.",
  importance:"The right to strike had come in 1864; full legalization of unions took two more decades of Third Republic politics. The 93-year arc from prohibition (1791) to legalization (1884) is the measure of how long the 'free labor market' was constructed by criminal law — and the CGT (1895) and French syndicalism grew quickly in the opened space.",
  impact:{
    labor:"French organized labor surfaces from a century underground.",
    regulation:"Completes Europe's great reversal from criminalizing to regulating worker organization.",
    society:"Mass union federations become permanent actors in European politics." },
  causes:["lechapelier","tradeunionact1871"], effects:["ilo"] },

{ id:"bismarck", year:1883, date:"1883–1889", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"Bismarck Invents Social Insurance",
  wiki:"State Socialism (Germany)", gallery:["Otto von Bismarck","Welfare state"],
  summary:"Germany builds the world's first social insurance system — health (1883), accident (1884), old-age (1889) — to undercut the socialists it was simultaneously banning.",
  importance:"Bismarck paired the Anti-Socialist Laws with welfare provision: repress the movement, deliver its demands. The world's first comprehensive social insurance became the model for welfare states across Europe — and a measure of American exceptionalism, since the U.S. equivalent (Social Security, 1935) arrived fifty years later. The strategy also institutionalized a fateful by-product: state insurance requires state records of every worker's wages, employment, and health.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The welfare state is founded — as counter-revolutionary statecraft.",
    labor:"Workers gain material security as a right of status, not charity.",
    surveillance:"Social insurance creates the registered, numbered worker — the administrative identity later generalized by Social Security numbers.",
    government:"Demonstrates the durable formula: welfare concessions as the price of political stability." },
  causes:["manifesto1848"], effects:["ssa1935","beveridge"] },

{ id:"standardtime", year:1884, date:"1884", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"The World Adopts Standard Time",
  wiki:"International Meridian Conference", gallery:["Time zone","Royal Observatory, Greenwich"],
  summary:"The International Meridian Conference fixes Greenwich as zero and divides the planet into time zones — railway and telegraph coordination made global.",
  importance:"Railways could not run safely on hundreds of local solar times; telegraphs made synchronization possible; the 1884 Washington conference made it policy. Mumford's point about the clock reaches planetary completion here: abstract mechanical time, once a monastic discipline, becomes the coordinate system of global commerce and labor. Every timetable, time-stamped record, and network log inherits this grid.",
  impact:{
    technology:"A single global temporal infrastructure — prerequisite for every synchronized network since.",
    labor:"The standardized shift, schedule, and time-clock discipline labor worldwide.",
    government:"International technical coordination emerges as a quiet new form of governance." },
  causes:["clock","railway","telegraph"], effects:[] },

{ id:"haymarket", year:1886, date:"May 1886", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"Haymarket & the Birth of May Day",
  wiki:"Haymarket affair", gallery:["Eight-hour day","International Workers' Day"],
  summary:"A bomb at a Chicago eight-hour-day rally brings a show trial and four hangings — and gives the world's workers their holiday.",
  importance:"The May 1886 strike wave for the eight-hour day drew hundreds of thousands; the Haymarket bombing and the hanging of four anarchists on flimsy evidence made it global memory. The Second International (1889) declared May 1 International Workers' Day in commemoration — observed nearly everywhere except the United States, where the date was deliberately displaced. The AFL, founded the same year, channeled American labor toward craft pragmatism; the martyrs channeled everyone else toward May Day.",
  impact:{
    labor:"The eight-hour movement acquires its martyrs; May Day becomes labor's global holiday.",
    society:"The anarchist scare inaugurates America's recurring red scares.",
    government:"Political trials of labor radicals enter the American repertoire — Debs, Sacco and Vanzetti, and the Palmer Raids follow.",
    regulation:"The eight-hour demand, here a hanging offense by association, becomes federal law within two generations (FLSA, 1938)." },
  causes:["railroadstrike1877","firstinternational","deirstrike"], effects:["pullman","flsa"] },

{ id:"kodak", year:1888, date:"1888", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"The Kodak Camera",
  wiki:"Kodak", gallery:["George Eastman","Box camera"],
  summary:"'You press the button, we do the rest.' Eastman puts photography in everyone's hands — and privacy law is invented in response.",
  importance:"The Kodak made photographing strangers effortless, and the 'kodaker' lurking outside weddings and beaches became a press scandal. Two Boston lawyers answered: Warren and Brandeis's 'The Right to Privacy' (1890) — the foundational document of American privacy law — was provoked directly by the camera and yellow journalism. The pair (gadget, then doctrine) is this museum's cleanest specimen of technology creating a legal idea: the right to be let alone.",
  impact:{
    technology:"Image capture is democratized — the ancestor of the camera phone in every pocket.",
    regulation:"Directly triggers the invention of privacy as a legal right.",
    society:"The boundary between public and private life becomes a technological negotiation, permanently.",
    surveillance:"Cheap photography arms not only citizens but detectives, employers, and states." },
  causes:["edison"], effects:["brandeis","cameraphone"] },

{ id:"hertz", year:1888, date:"1888", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"Hertz Confirms Electromagnetic Waves",
  wiki:"Heinrich Hertz", gallery:["Electromagnetic radiation","James Clerk Maxwell"],
  summary:"Hertz experimentally proves Maxwell's invisible waves — 'of no use whatsoever,' he says. Radio is seven years away.",
  importance:"Maxwell's equations had predicted electromagnetic waves; Hertz generated and detected them, then famously declared the discovery useless. Marconi disagreed within a decade. The episode is the museum's standing reminder that the regulatory future of a technology — spectrum law, broadcast licensing, the FCC — can be entirely invisible at the moment of scientific birth. No regulation ever touched Hertz's waves; everything regulated what people built on them.",
  impact:{
    technology:"The scientific foundation of all wireless communication.",
    society:"Pure research's unforeseeable consequences become a recurring policy parable.",
    communications:"Opens the spectrum — a new commons whose enclosure and licensing will occupy the next century." },
  causes:[], effects:["marconi"] },

{ id:"strowger", year:1891, date:"1889–1892", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"The Strowger Switch",
  wiki:"Strowger switch", gallery:["Almon Brown Strowger","Telephone exchange"],
  summary:"An undertaker, convinced operators are diverting his calls to rivals, invents automatic switching — surveillance distrust as the mother of automation.",
  importance:"Almon Strowger's automatic exchange (patented 1891, first commercial installation at La Porte, Indiana, 1892) removed the human operator from the connection — born, by legend and likely fact, from his suspicion that an operator was steering his customers to a competitor. It created the first technical alternative to Bell's switching; AT&T licensed it in 1916. The automation of the operator is an early, complete case study: a trust problem solved by machinery, at the eventual cost of an entire occupation.",
  impact:{
    technology:"Automatic switching — the telephone network begins to dial itself.",
    labor:"Begins the long automation of the telephone operator, one of the great women's occupations.",
    surveillance:"Designed explicitly to remove a human intermediary who could listen and divert — privacy by architecture, 1891.",
    regulation:"Independent switching technology underpins the later argument that the network need not be one company's property (Carterfone, 1968)." },
  causes:["bell"], effects:["carterfone"] },

{ id:"shermanact", year:1890, date:"1890", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Sherman Antitrust Act",
  wiki:"Sherman Antitrust Act", gallery:["Standard Oil","John Sherman","Trust (business)"],
  summary:"Congress answers the trusts — Standard Oil, sugar, whiskey — with the founding charter of antitrust law.",
  importance:"The Sherman Act made combinations in restraint of trade and monopolization federal offenses, answering the late-19th-century trust formations. Its first decades were ironic — courts applied it more readily to unions than to corporations — but it became the legal instrument that broke Standard Oil (1911), pressured AT&T (1913, 1956, 1984), pursued IBM and Microsoft, and now confronts the platforms. Adam Smith's conspiracy warning, 114 years later, in statutory form.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Antitrust is founded — the state's standing claim to restructure private economic power.",
    power:"Concentrated capital acquires a permanent legal adversary, episodically awakened.",
    labor:"Early enforcement against unions (In re Debs, Pullman) shows neutral text bent by judicial climate.",
    government:"Economic structure becomes a question of law, not just market outcome." },
  causes:["wealthofnations","westernunion","eastindia"], effects:["standardoil","clayton","attbreakup","microsoftcase","googlecase"] },

{ id:"hollerith", year:1890, date:"1890", era:4, cat:"computing",
  title:"Hollerith's Punch Cards Count America",
  wiki:"Herman Hollerith", gallery:["Tabulating machine","Punched card","IBM"],
  summary:"The 1890 census is tabulated by machine — population data becomes machine-readable, and the company that becomes IBM is born.",
  importance:"The 1880 census had taken eight years to count; Hollerith's electric tabulators, reading punched cards descended from Jacquard's, finished 1890's in a fraction of the time. His Tabulating Machine Company merged into what became IBM (1924). Machine-readable population data transformed state capacity — for administration, and for darker uses: IBM's German subsidiary's machines would later serve the Nazi regime's registries. The punch card is where the census, the corporation, and the computer first meet.",
  impact:{
    computing:"Data processing becomes an industry; the punch card reigns for seventy years.",
    surveillance:"Population data, once tabulated by machine, can be sorted, selected, and targeted at scale.",
    government:"The statistical state acquires industrial machinery.",
    power:"Begins IBM's dominance of information processing — and the antitrust attention that follows it from 1936 to 1982." },
  causes:["jacquard","uscensus1790"], effects:["ibmnazi","attdecree1956","eniac"] },

{ id:"brandeis", year:1890, date:"1890", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"'The Right to Privacy'",
  wiki:"The Right to Privacy (article)", gallery:["Louis Brandeis","Samuel D. Warren II","Harvard Law Review"],
  summary:"Warren and Brandeis, provoked by the Kodak and the gossip press, argue for a legal right 'to be let alone.'",
  importance:"The most influential law review article ever written distilled a new harm — 'instantaneous photographs and newspaper enterprise have invaded the sacred precincts of private and domestic life' — into a proposed common-law right. Over seventy years it seeded the privacy torts, then constitutional privacy doctrine (Griswold, 1965), and stands at the head of the lineage running to the FIPPs, the EU Data Protection Directive, and GDPR. Privacy law's origin is a complaint about a camera.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Privacy enters law as a named right with a theory behind it.",
    surveillance:"Defines the template: each new observation technology renews the Warren-Brandeis argument.",
    society:"'The right to be let alone' becomes the phrase with which citizens answer cameras, wiretaps, and databases alike." },
  causes:["kodak"], effects:["katz","fipps","gdpr"] },

{ id:"marconi", year:1895, date:"1895–1901", era:4, cat:"communications",
  title:"Marconi's Wireless",
  wiki:"Guglielmo Marconi", gallery:["Wireless telegraphy","Marconi Company"],
  summary:"Radio telegraphy works — across a room, then the Channel, then the Atlantic (1901). The spectrum becomes territory.",
  importance:"Marconi commercialized Hertz's 'useless' waves into maritime communication and a near-monopoly operating company. Wireless created an unprecedented regulatory object: a shared, invisible medium where one transmitter's freedom is another's interference. Patent wars (resolved into the RCA pool, 1919) and maritime chaos followed — and when the Titanic's distress calls drowned in amateur traffic, regulation arrived within four months.",
  impact:{
    communications:"Communication cuts the wire — ships, then continents, then everyone.",
    regulation:"Spectrum scarcity invents a new kind of law: licensing access to physics itself.",
    technology:"The radio industry incubates the vacuum-tube electronics that become broadcasting and computing.",
    government:"Navies and empires seize wireless as strategic infrastructure from the first spark." },
  causes:["hertz","westernunion"], effects:["titanic","audion","kdka"] },

{ id:"pullman", year:1894, date:"1894–1895", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"Pullman, In re Debs & the Injunction",
  wiki:"Pullman Strike", gallery:["Eugene V. Debs","Pullman Company"],
  summary:"A national rail boycott is broken by federal troops and a court injunction — which the Supreme Court unanimously blesses.",
  importance:"The Pullman boycott, led by Eugene Debs's American Railway Union, halted rail traffic across half the country until President Cleveland sent the army — over the Illinois governor's objection — and a federal injunction criminalized the strike's continuation. In re Debs (1895) made the labor injunction the employer's standard weapon for forty years, until Norris-LaGuardia (1932) disarmed it. Debs left prison a socialist; Labor Day, established as a federal holiday the same year, was the consolation prize.",
  impact:{
    labor:"The injunction era: courts as the front line against strikes.",
    regulation:"Sherman Act and equity power turned against unions — law's neutrality tested and found wanting.",
    government:"Federal military intervention in strikes is constitutionally ratified.",
    society:"Debs and American socialism rise from the wreckage." },
  causes:["railroadstrike1877","haymarket","shermanact"], effects:["wagneract"] },

{ id:"plessy", year:1896, date:"1896", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"Plessy v. Ferguson",
  wiki:"Plessy v. Ferguson", gallery:["Jim Crow laws","Racial segregation in the United States","John Marshall Harlan"],
  summary:"The Supreme Court ratifies 'separate but equal' — the constitutional foundation of Jim Crow for fifty-eight years.",
  importance:"Plessy constitutionalized segregation, completing the betrayal begun when Reconstruction ended in 1877. For Black labor, the consequences were total: disenfranchisement, exclusion from trades and unions, sharecropping and convict leasing enforced by law and terror. The decision stood until Brown v. Board of Education (1954) — and its shadow lies across every labor statistic in the American galleries of this museum.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Legal segregation receives constitutional sanction.",
    labor:"Black workers are systematically excluded from the era's labor gains — and many unions cooperated.",
    society:"Jim Crow becomes the architecture of Southern life and a driver of the Great Migration.",
    government:"Demonstrates the Court's capacity to entrench, as well as dismantle, caste." },
  causes:["emancipation"], effects:["civilrightsact"] },

{ id:"taylorism", year:1911, date:"1903–1911", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"Scientific Management",
  wiki:"Scientific management", gallery:["Frederick Winslow Taylor","Time and motion study"],
  summary:"Frederick Taylor's stopwatch makes the worker's every motion an object of measurement — workplace surveillance acquires a science.",
  importance:"Shop Management (1903) and The Principles of Scientific Management (1911) proposed separating thinking from doing: managers measure, plan, and prescribe; workers execute the one best way. Taylorism begins the workplace-surveillance tradition that runs unbroken through time-and-motion study, the punch clock, keystroke logging, and algorithmic management of warehouse and gig labor — a domain that remains, as the source timelines note, largely unregulated through the present.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Craft knowledge is expropriated into management's clipboard; deskilling becomes method.",
    surveillance:"The measured worker — Taylor's stopwatch is the ancestor of the productivity dashboard.",
    society:"Efficiency becomes an ideology reaching far beyond the factory.",
    technology:"Management itself becomes a 'technology,' exported worldwide from Ford's lines to Soviet planning." },
  causes:["clock","ford"], effects:["gigeconomy"] },

{ id:"wright", year:1903, date:"1903", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"First Powered Flight",
  wiki:"Wright Flyer", gallery:["Wright brothers","Kitty Hawk, North Carolina"],
  summary:"The Wright brothers fly at Kitty Hawk — beginning the technology that will transform commerce, war, and the view from above.",
  importance:"Aviation's regulatory and surveillance career began almost immediately: aerial reconnaissance in WWI, air-mail and licensing regimes in the 1920s, strategic bombing in WWII, and ultimately the satellite's omniscient descendant gaze. The airplane also created one of the century's emblematic skilled workforces — and, in 1981, the stage for PATCO, the strike whose crushing defined an era of labor relations.",
  impact:{
    technology:"The third dimension opens to transport and observation.",
    government:"Air power reshapes war and statecraft; the view from above becomes a state prerogative.",
    labor:"Aviation builds new skilled trades — pilots, machinists, controllers — central to 20th-century labor history." },
  causes:[], effects:["patco"] },

{ id:"audion", year:1906, date:"1906", era:4, cat:"technology",
  title:"De Forest's Audion",
  wiki:"Audion", gallery:["Lee de Forest","Vacuum tube","Triode"],
  summary:"The triode vacuum tube: amplification. Without it, no broadcasting, no long-distance telephony, no electronic computing.",
  importance:"Fleming's diode (1904) could detect signals; De Forest's third electrode could amplify them. The Audion made voice radio, transcontinental telephony (1915), and ultimately electronic computers possible. As the source timeline puts it: without the Audion, no broadcasting industry, no 1927 Radio Act, no 1934 Communications Act, no FCC. The same year, Fessenden made the first known audio broadcast — voice and music over the winter sea to startled ship operators.",
  impact:{
    technology:"Electronic amplification — the enabling component of the century's communications and computing.",
    communications:"Voice conquers both wire (coast-to-coast, 1915) and air (broadcasting, 1920).",
    regulation:"The invention itself was never regulated; the industries it enabled summoned entire agencies — the typical pattern." },
  causes:["marconi"], effects:["kdka","eniac"] },

{ id:"lochner", year:1905, date:"1905", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"Lochner v. New York",
  wiki:"Lochner v. New York", gallery:["Supreme Court of the United States","Bakery"],
  summary:"The Supreme Court strikes down a 10-hour law for bakers — 'liberty of contract' against labor legislation, for thirty years.",
  importance:"Lochner made freedom of contract a constitutional weapon against hours and wages laws, defining an era in which courts voided much labor legislation. Muller v. Oregon (1908) carved out protection for women — the familiar wedge — but the doctrine held until West Coast Hotel v. Parrish (1937) capitulated to the New Deal. Lochner remains the byword for judicially imposed laissez-faire, and the IWW (founded 1905, the same year) the byword for the radical answer.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Constitutionalized laissez-faire blocks the labor-law agenda for a generation.",
    labor:"Hours legislation survives only where courts deem workers 'dependent' — protection as condescension.",
    government:"The judiciary reveals itself as the decisive arena of American labor policy." },
  causes:["statutelabourers"], effects:["wagneract","flsa"] },

{ id:"triangle", year:1911, date:"March 25, 1911", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"The Triangle Shirtwaist Fire",
  wiki:"Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire", gallery:["International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union","Frances Perkins"],
  summary:"146 garment workers — mostly young immigrant women — die behind locked doors in Manhattan. The witnesses build the New Deal.",
  importance:"Two years after the 'Uprising of the 20,000' shirtwaist strike had demanded safer shops, fire trapped Triangle's workers on the ninth floor; the doors were locked against union organizers and theft. Frances Perkins watched the bodies fall — and as FDR's Labor Secretary would carry the memory into the Social Security Act and FLSA. New York's Factory Investigating Commission produced the era's strongest workplace codes. The fire is the American pattern in miniature: documented horror converting, at last, into law.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Galvanizes garment unionism and the modern workplace-safety movement.",
    regulation:"New York's factory codes become the template for state and ultimately federal safety law (OSHA, 1970).",
    society:"Industrial death becomes front-page moral scandal — publicity as regulatory force.",
    government:"The investigating commission model — testimony, documentation, statute — is perfected here." },
  causes:["lowell","factoryact1833"], effects:["wagneract","oshact","ranaplaza"] },

{ id:"standardoil", year:1911, date:"1911", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"Standard Oil Is Broken Up",
  wiki:"Standard Oil", gallery:["John D. Rockefeller","Ida Tarbell"],
  summary:"The Supreme Court dissolves Rockefeller's trust into 34 companies — the precedent for corporate divestiture.",
  importance:"Two decades after the Sherman Act, and aided by Ida Tarbell's muckraking exposé, the Court ordered history's most famous breakup (American Tobacco fell the same year). The case established that the state could dismember a dominant firm — the precedent invoked against AT&T in 1984 and debated in every platform case since. It also announced the 'rule of reason,' the interpretive lens that has governed — and often narrowed — antitrust ever since.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Divestiture proven as a working remedy, not just a threat.",
    power:"The trust era's emblem is dismantled — though its fragments (Exxon, Mobil, Chevron) grow vast again.",
    society:"Investigative journalism demonstrates its regulatory power — Tarbell's series is the ancestor of every tech exposé.",
    government:"Antitrust becomes a presidential-scale political instrument." },
  causes:["shermanact"], effects:["attbreakup","microsoftcase"] },

{ id:"titanic", year:1912, date:"April–August 1912", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Titanic & the Radio Act of 1912",
  wiki:"Sinking of the Titanic", gallery:["RMS Titanic","Radio Act of 1912","Wireless telegraphy"],
  summary:"Confused and crowded airwaves hamper the rescue; four months later, Congress licenses the spectrum. The fastest invention-to-regulation chain in this museum.",
  importance:"Amateur transmissions and uncoordinated operators muddled the Titanic's distress traffic; some nearby ships' operators were simply off duty. The Radio Act of August 1912 imposed licensing, frequency allocation, and 24-hour watch requirements. Disaster-to-statute in four months — the clearest case on record of visible, politically urgent failure producing immediate regulation, against the usual pattern of decades-long lag. The EU's 18-month sprint from ChatGPT to the AI Act is this chain's modern echo.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Spectrum licensing begins; the state becomes radio's landlord.",
    communications:"Maritime radio is professionalized and standardized worldwide.",
    society:"A single broadcast catastrophe teaches the public what communication failure costs.",
    government:"Establishes the template the 1927 Radio Act and FCC inherit." },
  causes:["marconi"], effects:["radioact1927"] },

{ id:"kingsbury", year:1913, date:"1913", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Kingsbury Commitment",
  wiki:"Kingsbury Commitment", gallery:["AT&T Corporation","Theodore Newton Vail"],
  summary:"Facing antitrust threat, AT&T agrees to interconnection and divests Western Union — purchasing seventy years of regulated monopoly.",
  importance:"Theodore Vail's AT&T had been swallowing independents under the slogan 'One System, One Policy, Universal Service.' The Justice Department's Sherman Act threats produced not a breakup but a bargain: AT&T sold its Western Union stake, allowed independents to interconnect, and in exchange was left standing as a regulated monopoly. The model governed American telephony until 1984 — monopoly tolerated, supervised, and ultimately dismantled by the framework Kingsbury began.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The regulated-monopoly settlement: the century's defining communications-governance model.",
    communications:"Universal service becomes the network's public justification.",
    power:"Demonstrates the negotiated, rather than adjudicated, taming of concentrated capital.",
    government:"Regulation by consent decree and commitment letter enters the toolkit." },
  causes:["bell","shermanact","westernunion"], effects:["communicationsact","attdecree1956","attbreakup"] },

{ id:"ford", year:1913, date:"1913–1914", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"The Assembly Line & the Five-Dollar Day",
  wiki:"Assembly line", gallery:["Ford Model T","Highland Park Ford Plant","Henry Ford"],
  summary:"Ford's moving line cuts Model T assembly from hours to minutes; doubling pay to $5 a day cuts the turnover the line created.",
  importance:"Highland Park fused Taylor's measurement with the conveyor's relentless pace — and workers fled it in droves until Ford doubled wages, with the company's Sociological Department inspecting workers' homes and habits as the price of the premium. Fordism — high output, high wages, intense discipline, surveillance of private life — became the dominant production model of the century, exported everywhere from Detroit to the Soviet plans it inspired.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Mass-production work is born: well paid, stupefying, and surveilled — the Fordist bargain.",
    surveillance:"The Sociological Department polices workers' households — employer surveillance beyond the factory gate.",
    society:"Mass production requires mass consumption; the worker is re-imagined as customer.",
    technology:"Continuous-flow production becomes the century's industrial paradigm." },
  causes:["taylorism","watt"], effects:["flint","treatyofdetroit"] },

{ id:"clayton", year:1914, date:"1914", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Clayton Act & the FTC",
  wiki:"Federal Trade Commission", gallery:["Clayton Antitrust Act of 1914","Woodrow Wilson"],
  summary:"Congress patches the Sherman Act, declares labor 'not a commodity,' and creates the FTC — whose Section 5 becomes America's de facto privacy regulator.",
  importance:"The Clayton Act addressed Sherman's gaps (mergers, interlocking directorates) and declared that 'the labor of a human being is not a commodity' — partially exempting unions from antitrust, on paper. The FTC Act's Section 5 ban on 'unfair or deceptive practices' proved the more protean creation: a century later it is the primary federal instrument of consumer-privacy enforcement, the basis of the Facebook and Google consent decrees, in the absence of any comprehensive U.S. privacy statute.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The administrative agency model arrives in competition and consumer protection.",
    labor:"Statutory recognition that labor is not an article of commerce — honored unevenly ever after.",
    surveillance:"Section 5 becomes, by default, the closest thing America has to a privacy law.",
    government:"Expert commissions begin their long career as the fourth branch." },
  causes:["shermanact"], effects:["ftcfacebook"] },

{ id:"wwi", year:1914, date:"1914–1918", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"The First World War",
  wiki:"World War I", gallery:["Trench warfare","Zimmermann Telegram","Women in World War I"],
  summary:"Industrial war: 17–19 million dead, four empires destroyed, women in the factories, signals intelligence institutionalized, and propaganda made a science.",
  importance:"The war transformed every domain this museum tracks. Signals intelligence expanded on all sides (the intercepted Zimmermann Telegram helped bring America in), establishing the institutions that became peacetime SIGINT and eventually the NSA. War economies demonstrated total state direction of labor; women entered industrial work in the millions. The Creel Committee ran propaganda at scale, teaching a generation — including Edward Bernays — that mass opinion could be engineered. The Espionage Act (1917) remains on the books, used against leakers a century later.",
  impact:{
    surveillance:"Modern SIGINT institutionalized; censorship and espionage statutes erected — and never fully dismantled.",
    labor:"Total mobilization shows labor's strategic power; the 8-hour day becomes the postwar international standard.",
    society:"Mass propaganda is invented as a state function.",
    government:"Four empires collapse; the war's settlement creates the ILO and the conditions for the next war." },
  causes:[], effects:["russianrev","ilo","nsa","bernays"] },

{ id:"russianrev", year:1917, date:"1917", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"The Russian Revolution",
  wiki:"Russian Revolution", gallery:["Vladimir Lenin","October Revolution","Cheka"],
  summary:"The Tsar falls in February; the Bolsheviks seize October. The world's first communist state — and within weeks, the Cheka.",
  importance:"The century's most consequential revolution established a state claiming labor's name — decreeing the 8-hour day immediately — and built, almost as quickly, the Cheka, ancestor of the OGPU, NKVD, and KGB: the most elaborate political-surveillance apparatus yet constructed. The Soviet project shaped global labor standards through competition, inspired movements and parties worldwide through the Comintern (1919), and demonstrated in the Gulag and the purges the extremes of state-coerced labor. Its 1991 dissolution closes this museum's longest single arc.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Labor's revolution delivers the 8-hour day — and ultimately the Gulag: both poles of the state-labor relationship.",
    surveillance:"The modern total-surveillance state is pioneered — informers, internal passports, political police.",
    government:"A third of humanity comes to be ruled by parties claiming this lineage; the Cold War organizes the century.",
    society:"Welfare-state competition between blocs benefits workers on both sides of the divide." },
  causes:["manifesto1848","serfemancipation","pariscommune","wwi"], effects:["stalin","coldwar","solidarity"] },

{ id:"ilo", year:1919, date:"1919", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The International Labour Organization",
  wiki:"International Labour Organization", gallery:["Treaty of Versailles","League of Nations"],
  summary:"The Versailles settlement creates the first international labor regulator — its first convention: the 8-hour day.",
  importance:"Postwar fear of revolutionary labor unrest produced the first specialized international agency, on the premise that 'peace can be established only if it is based upon social justice.' Hours of Work Convention No. 1 (1919) made the 8-hour day an international standard. The ILO outlived the League, joined the UN system, and its conventions on forced labor, child labor, and freedom of association remain the closest thing to a global labor constitution. Mexico's 1917 constitution — Article 123's eight-hour day, minimum wage, and right to strike — had already shown labor rights written into fundamental law.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"Labor standards become international law — tripartite, conventional, and chronically under-enforced.",
    labor:"The 8-hour day, fought for since Haymarket, becomes the declared global norm.",
    government:"International technical organizations emerge as a standing layer of governance." },
  causes:["wwi","firstinternational","haymarket","waldeckrousseau"], effects:["udhr"] },

{ id:"nineteenth", year:1920, date:"1920", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Nineteenth Amendment",
  wiki:"Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution", gallery:["Women's suffrage in the United States","Suffragette"],
  summary:"American women win the vote — seventy-two years after Seneca Falls.",
  importance:"The suffrage victory, accelerated by women's wartime labor, completed the demand drafted in 1848 and rebalanced the politics behind every subsequent labor and welfare statute. Women's organizations — the WTUL, the garment unions, the settlement movement — had fused suffrage and labor causes; their heirs (Frances Perkins above all) would write much of the New Deal.",
  impact:{
    society:"Half the population enters the electorate; the reform coalitions of the next decades are transformed.",
    labor:"Women's labor activism gains direct political leverage.",
    government:"Constitutional amendment proves still possible as a vehicle of mass-movement victory." },
  causes:["senecafalls","wwi"], effects:["ssa1935"] },

{ id:"kdka", year:1920, date:"November 2, 1920", era:4, cat:"communications",
  title:"KDKA: Broadcasting Begins",
  wiki:"KDKA (AM)", gallery:["Golden Age of Radio","Crystal radio"],
  summary:"Pittsburgh's KDKA airs the Harding–Cox election returns on a regular schedule — commercial broadcasting is born.",
  importance:"Radio had been point-to-point; KDKA made it one-to-everyone, and the receiver-buying public materialized within months. Two years later AT&T's WEAF sold the first paid radio advertisement (August 28, 1922) — the innovation that set broadcasting's economic logic, and through it the regulatory frameworks of 1927, 1934, the Fairness Doctrine, and the 1996 Act. The age of mass media, audience markets, and spectrum politics opens here.",
  impact:{
    communications:"Mass broadcasting: one voice, millions of ears, in real time.",
    society:"The shared national audience — and the national advertiser — come into being.",
    regulation:"Station proliferation produces spectrum chaos that the 1912 Act cannot handle, forcing the 1927 Radio Act.",
    technology:"The advertising-supported model invented at WEAF becomes the business plan of radio, TV, and eventually the internet." },
  causes:["audion","marconi","edison"], effects:["radioact1927","attention"] },

{ id:"attention", year:1923, date:"1923–1929", era:4, cat:"surveillance",
  title:"The Attention Industry Is Born",
  wiki:"Nielsen Holdings", gallery:["Audience measurement","Advertising"],
  summary:"Crossley's ratings (1923), Starch's readership research (1924), Nielsen (1929): the systematic measurement of human attention begins.",
  importance:"Once broadcasting sold audiences to advertisers, the audience had to be counted. Archibald Crossley's telephone surveys began systematic audience measurement; A.C. Nielsen built the company that would meter radio (1942) and television (1950) and give its name to the ratings. This is the founding of the attention-measurement industry that runs continuously to Google Analytics and engagement dashboards — and, as the source timeline notes, no comprehensive U.S. regulation of audience measurement and behavioral inference has ever been passed.",
  impact:{
    surveillance:"Human attention becomes a measured, traded commodity — the quiet founding of surveillance capitalism's logic.",
    society:"Culture begins optimizing for what measures well.",
    regulation:"A century of regulatory silence — the gap in which the digital attention economy later grows.",
    technology:"Sampling, panels, and ratings anticipate the metrics-driven design of the platform era." },
  causes:["kdka"], effects:["adwords","likebutton"] },

{ id:"bernays", year:1928, date:"1923–1928", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"Bernays & the Engineering of Consent",
  wiki:"Edward Bernays", gallery:["Propaganda (book)","Public relations"],
  summary:"Freud's nephew, trained on wartime propaganda, founds public relations — Crystallizing Public Opinion (1923), then Propaganda (1928).",
  importance:"Bernays translated the Creel Committee's wartime lessons into peacetime practice: opinion could be engineered through symbols, experts, and staged events ('torches of freedom' made cigarettes a suffrage statement). His books formalized the discipline underlying advertising, PR, and political communication for the century — the intellectual infrastructure of the attention economy. No regulation ever touched the practice itself; the FTC polices only its most literal deceptions.",
  impact:{
    society:"Mass persuasion becomes a profession with a theory.",
    communications:"Media are reconceived as instruments for shaping, not just informing, publics.",
    government:"Democracies adopt — and never relinquish — the machinery of managed opinion.",
    regulation:"The persuasion industries remain essentially unregulated, a silence stretching to micro-targeting and dark patterns." },
  causes:["wwi","attention"], effects:["cambridgeanalytica"] },

{ id:"radioact1927", year:1927, date:"1927", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Radio Act of 1927",
  wiki:"Radio Act of 1927", gallery:["Federal Radio Commission","NBC"],
  summary:"Spectrum chaos and network consolidation (NBC 1926, CBS 1927) force a new framework: licensed broadcasters as public trustees.",
  importance:"The 1912 Act was built for ships, not broadcasting; by the mid-1920s stations drowned each other out and a court ruling stripped the Commerce Department's authority. The 1927 Act created the Federal Radio Commission and the public-interest licensing framework — broadcasters as trustees of a public resource — that still governs American broadcasting. Farnsworth demonstrated all-electronic television the same year; the framework would be waiting for it.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The public-trustee model: licenses in exchange for public-interest obligations.",
    communications:"Order imposed on the spectrum; the network era is ratified rather than reversed.",
    government:"The FRC is the FCC's direct parent; broadcast regulation acquires its permanent agency.",
    society:"Decisions about who may speak to millions become administrative law." },
  causes:["titanic","kdka","marconi"], effects:["communicationsact","fairnessdoctrine"] },

{ id:"crash1929", year:1929, date:"1929", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"The Crash & the Great Depression",
  wiki:"Wall Street Crash of 1929", gallery:["Great Depression","Dust Bowl","Bank run"],
  summary:"The bubble bursts; unemployment reaches a quarter of the workforce; the political answer remakes the state's relationship to labor and markets.",
  importance:"The Crash and the Depression that followed radicalized politics worldwide — toward the New Deal in America, Popular Fronts in Europe, and fascism in Germany. The regulatory harvest was immense: securities law (1933–34), deposit insurance, and the entire New Deal labor settlement. The South Sea Bubble's cycle — mania, collapse, statute — replayed at world scale, and the welfare state Bismarck had pioneered became, under crisis, the democratic norm.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The Securities Acts and SEC found modern financial regulation.",
    labor:"Mass unemployment converts labor's demands into governing policy.",
    society:"Laissez-faire loses its century-long presumption of legitimacy.",
    government:"The interventionist state becomes the democratic standard — and the autocracies' foil." },
  causes:["southsea","voc"], effects:["wagneract","ssa1935","hitler"] },

{ id:"stalin", year:1930, date:"1928–1938", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"Stalin: Five-Year Plans, Famine & Terror",
  wiki:"Joseph Stalin", gallery:["Gulag","Holodomor","First five-year plan"],
  summary:"Forced collectivization, the Holodomor's millions, the Great Purge, and a Gulag through which 18 million pass — coerced labor at totalitarian scale.",
  importance:"Stalin's industrialization mobilized labor by coercion and propaganda at once: the Stakhanovite hero-worker on the poster, the prisoner in the Gulag building the canal. Collectivization produced famine killing millions, above all in Ukraine. The system demonstrates the extreme pole of state labor coercion in the modern age — and its surveillance apparatus, perfected by the NKVD, became the model and the adversary around which Western intelligence organized for fifty years.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Forced labor at industrial scale — the Gulag as economic institution.",
    surveillance:"The informer state perfected: denunciation as civic duty, terror as administration.",
    government:"Totalitarian planning's human cost becomes the century's darkest demonstration of unchecked state power over labor.",
    society:"The purge and the show trial enter the world's political vocabulary." },
  causes:["russianrev"], effects:["coldwar"] },

{ id:"hitler", year:1933, date:"1933", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"The Nazi Seizure of Power",
  wiki:"Adolf Hitler's rise to power", gallery:["Nazi Germany","German Labour Front","Reichstag fire"],
  summary:"Hitler is appointed Chancellor; within months, unions are destroyed, parties banned, and the surveillance state armed with card files.",
  importance:"Among the regime's first acts was the destruction of independent unions, absorbed into the German Labour Front. The Depression's politics, Versailles's legacy, and elite miscalculation delivered the state to a movement that would deploy forced labor in the millions and genocide administered with bureaucratic precision — including IBM Hollerith machines, leased through its German subsidiary, used in census and registry operations. The catastrophe became the negative foundation of postwar human rights, German constitutionalism, and ultimately European data-protection law.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Free labor movements annihilated overnight; forced labor becomes a pillar of the war economy.",
    surveillance:"Registries, censuses, and punch cards repurposed for persecution — the lesson cited in Germany's 1983 census ruling.",
    government:"Demonstrates democratic collapse into total state — the scenario all postwar constitutional design guards against.",
    regulation:"Its memory produces the UDHR, the German Basic Law, and the informational self-determination doctrine behind GDPR." },
  causes:["crash1929","wwi"], effects:["ibmnazi","ww2","volkszahlung"] },

{ id:"ibmnazi", year:1933, date:"1933–1945", era:4, cat:"surveillance",
  title:"IBM's Punch Cards & the Nazi Registries",
  wiki:"IBM and the Holocaust", gallery:["Dehomag","Punched card"],
  summary:"Hollerith machines, leased via IBM's German subsidiary Dehomag, serve the Nazi regime's censuses and registries.",
  importance:"The machines that counted America's census served Germany's racial state: census tabulation, registry-keeping, and administrative sorting at machine speed. No contemporaneous regulation existed or intervened. The episode became foundational to postwar data-protection thinking — cited specifically in the legislative history of Germany's 1983 Volkszählungsurteil — as the standing proof that population data, once collected, can be turned to any purpose a regime chooses.",
  impact:{
    surveillance:"The catastrophic proof-of-concept: neutral data infrastructure weaponized for persecution.",
    regulation:"Becomes the founding memory of European data protection — 'never again' rendered as data law.",
    technology:"Demonstrates that the dual-use problem is native to information technology, not an aberration.",
    society:"Corporate complicity in state atrocity enters the permanent ethical record of the technology industry." },
  causes:["hollerith","hitler"], effects:["volkszahlung","gdpr"] },

{ id:"communicationsact", year:1934, date:"1934", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Communications Act & the FCC",
  wiki:"Communications Act of 1934", gallery:["Federal Communications Commission"],
  summary:"Wire and wireless are unified under one statute and one agency — the foundational charter of American communications law for 62 years.",
  importance:"The Act merged the Radio Act's broadcast framework with the regulated-monopoly telephony model descended from Kingsbury, creating the Federal Communications Commission. It remained the foundational statute until 1996, and its categories — common carrier, broadcaster, public interest — still structure every American argument about networks, from the Fairness Doctrine to net neutrality. Ninety years of regulatory chain from de Forest's tube to this statute, as the source timeline traces.",
  impact:{
    regulation:"One agency, one statute: communications law gets its constitution.",
    communications:"The common-carrier and broadcast-trustee models are locked in for two generations.",
    government:"The FCC becomes the arena where every subsequent network technology — cable, satellite, internet — first meets the state." },
  causes:["radioact1927","kingsbury","westernunion","telegraph"], effects:["fairnessdoctrine","telecomact"] },

{ id:"wagneract", year:1935, date:"1935", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Wagner Act",
  wiki:"National Labor Relations Act of 1935", gallery:["National Labor Relations Board","Congress of Industrial Organizations"],
  summary:"The state, for once, takes labor's side: the right to organize and bargain collectively becomes federal law, with a board to enforce it.",
  importance:"Against the 4,000-year pattern this museum documents — Statute of Labourers to the injunction era — the National Labor Relations Act guaranteed organizing rights and outlawed employer interference, upheld by the Supreme Court's 1937 about-face in NLRB v. Jones & Laughlin. The CIO organized mass-production industry in its shelter; union density tripled in a decade. Taft-Hartley (1947) would claw back ground, but the Wagner framework remains American labor law's foundation — the great exception that proves the ancient rule.",
  impact:{
    labor:"The legal foundation of the American labor movement's golden age.",
    regulation:"Collective bargaining becomes administered public policy, not private war.",
    government:"The commerce clause, post-1937, underwrites the modern regulatory state.",
    society:"The mid-century middle class is built substantially on Wagner Act wages." },
  causes:["crash1929","pullman","triangle","lochner","tradeunionact1871","constitution"], effects:["flint","tafthartley","treatyofdetroit"] },

{ id:"ssa1935", year:1935, date:"1935", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"Social Security — and the Number",
  wiki:"Social Security Act", gallery:["Social Security number","Frances Perkins","New Deal"],
  summary:"America builds federal social insurance — and in doing so issues the identifier that becomes the de facto national ID.",
  importance:"Fifty years after Bismarck, the Depression forced American social insurance into existence under Frances Perkins's hand. The Act created the first mass federal individual-records system; the nine-digit Social Security number, intended for one program's bookkeeping, crept across five decades into employment, credit, tax, and identity itself. That identifier creep — convenience hardening into infrastructure — is among the museum's clearest specimens of surveillance by accretion, and helped provoke both the FCRA (1970) and the Privacy Act (1974).",
  impact:{
    regulation:"The American welfare state is founded.",
    surveillance:"The SSN becomes the master key of American records — never designed, merely accumulated.",
    labor:"Old-age insecurity, the worker's ancient fear, is partially nationalized.",
    society:"The numbered citizen arrives in America — each person a row in a federal ledger." },
  causes:["bismarck","crash1929","nineteenth","triangle"], effects:["privacyact","fcra"] },

{ id:"turing1936", year:1936, date:"1936", era:4, cat:"computing",
  title:"Turing's 'On Computable Numbers'",
  wiki:"Turing machine", gallery:["Alan Turing","Entscheidungsproblem"],
  summary:"To settle a question in logic, Alan Turing imagines a universal machine — and founds computer science before the computer exists.",
  importance:"Turing's paper defined computation itself: a simple abstract machine reading and writing symbols on a tape, capable — if universal — of simulating any other. Gleick places it at the heart of The Information: the discovery that computation is substrate-independent, that one machine can do what any machine can do. Every computer since is an engineering approximation of this 1936 thought experiment. Zuse was building his Z1 in Berlin the same year; theory and hardware were converging from both ends.",
  impact:{
    computing:"The theoretical foundation of all computing — universality, programs as data, the limits of the decidable.",
    technology:"Defines what machines can and cannot compute before any exist to try.",
    society:"The idea of the thinking machine acquires mathematical respectability — Turing himself will press the question in 1950." },
  causes:["babbage","lovelace"], effects:["ww2","turingtest","eniac"] },

{ id:"flint", year:1937, date:"1936–1937", era:4, cat:"labor",
  title:"The Flint Sit-Down Strike",
  wiki:"Flint sit-down strike", gallery:["United Auto Workers","General Motors"],
  summary:"Auto workers occupy GM's plants for 44 days; the company that ruled American industry signs with the UAW.",
  importance:"The sit-down — occupying the factory rather than picketing outside it — made strikebreaking impossible without visible violence against property and workers together. Michigan's governor refused to clear the plants by force; GM, the largest industrial corporation on earth, recognized the UAW. Union organization swept mass-production industry. The Memorial Day Massacre in Chicago months later showed the older pattern persisting; but after Flint, industrial unionism was a fact.",
  impact:{
    labor:"Mass-production unionism triumphs at the heart of American industry.",
    society:"The sit-down enters the repertoire of nonviolent mass action — borrowed later by the civil rights movement.",
    government:"State force withheld from strikebreaking for once — and the outcome was a contract, not a massacre." },
  causes:["wagneract","ford"], effects:["treatyofdetroit"] },

{ id:"waroftheworlds", year:1938, date:"October 30, 1938", era:4, cat:"communications",
  title:"The War of the Worlds Broadcast",
  wiki:"The War of the Worlds (1938 radio drama)", gallery:["Orson Welles","CBS"],
  summary:"Orson Welles's Martian invasion, staged as news bulletins, demonstrates broadcasting's power over mass belief.",
  importance:"The panic was smaller than legend claims, but the lesson was real and institutionalized: the Cantril study (1940) launched systematic mass-media-effects research, and broadcasters learned the format of credibility itself could be weaponized. Every subsequent anxiety about misinformation — from televised war to deepfakes — replays this Halloween experiment in the laboratory of the public mind.",
  impact:{
    society:"Mass media's power to manufacture reality becomes a documented, studied fact.",
    communications:"News conventions are revealed as a technology of belief, imitable and exploitable.",
    regulation:"No statute resulted — but media-effects research entered the regulatory conversation permanently." },
  causes:["kdka","bernays"], effects:["deepfakes"] },

{ id:"flsa", year:1938, date:"1938", era:4, cat:"law",
  title:"The Fair Labor Standards Act",
  wiki:"Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938", gallery:["Minimum wage in the United States","Child labour in the United States"],
  summary:"Federal minimum wage, the 40-hour week, and the end of child labor in interstate commerce — the demands of a century become statute.",
  importance:"The FLSA wrote into federal law what the Lowell operatives, the eight-hour movement, and Haymarket's martyrs had demanded: a wage floor, time-and-a-half past forty hours, and child labor's prohibition. Upheld in United States v. Darby (1941), it completed the constitutional revolution begun in 1937. Its exclusions — agricultural and domestic workers, occupations then largely Black and female — were the price Southern committee chairs exacted, a discrimination whose effects persist in the statute's gaps.",
  impact:{
    labor:"The wage floor and the weekend acquire federal force.",
    regulation:"Wage-and-hour law, the Statute of Labourers' mirror image, finally favors the worker.",
    society:"Childhood is legally separated from the labor market nationwide.",
    government:"Carve-outs for excluded occupations demonstrate how discrimination is engineered into neutral-seeming law." },
  causes:["haymarket","lochner","crash1929","factoryact1833"], effects:[] },

{ id:"ww2", year:1939, date:"1939–1945", era:4, cat:"power",
  title:"The Second World War",
  wiki:"World War II", gallery:["Bletchley Park","Colossus computer","Rosie the Riveter","Manhattan Project"],
  summary:"70–85 million dead. Codebreaking builds the first electronic computers; war work transforms labor; the postwar order is drafted in the rubble.",
  importance:"At Bletchley Park, breaking German ciphers produced the Bombe and then Colossus (1943) — the first large-scale electronic digital computer, secret for thirty years. The Manhattan Project showed what state-directed science could do; twelve million forced laborers showed what the Nazi economy ran on; Rosie the Riveter showed American industry staffed by women. From the war came the UN, the Bretton Woods order, the GI Bill, the Cold War intelligence apparatus — and the engineers who would build the computer industry. Vannevar Bush's 'As We May Think' (1945) sketched the information future from inside the war machine.",
  impact:{
    computing:"Electronic computing is born in secrecy — Colossus and ENIAC are war babies.",
    surveillance:"Allied SIGINT triumph institutionalizes peacetime signals intelligence — the NSA's direct ancestry.",
    labor:"Total mobilization, women's mass industrial entry, and forced labor at genocidal scale define the extremes.",
    government:"The national-security state and the postwar international order are both founded here.",
    society:"The Holocaust's bureaucratic machinery makes data, registry, and identity into permanent moral questions." },
  causes:["hitler","turing1936","wwi"], effects:["eniac","nsa","udhr","cctv"] },

{ id:"cctv", year:1942, date:"1942", era:4, cat:"surveillance",
  title:"The First CCTV",
  wiki:"Closed-circuit television", gallery:["Peenemünde Army Research Center","Surveillance camera"],
  summary:"Walter Bruch installs closed-circuit television at Peenemünde to watch V-2 rocket tests — the camera detaches from the human eye.",
  importance:"Born to observe rocket launches too dangerous to watch directly, CCTV migrated to commerce (America's Vericon, 1949, advertised as requiring no government permit — 'because none existed') and to public space: Trafalgar Square, 1960; Olean, New York, 1965; Times Square, 1973. The UK's mass deployment from 1985 made Britain the most-watched society on earth, eventually regulated under its Data Protection Acts. In the U.S., as the source timeline notes, no federal CCTV regulation has ever passed.",
  impact:{
    surveillance:"Continuous remote watching becomes a standing infrastructure of public and private space.",
    regulation:"Seven decades of deployment, near-zero comprehensive regulation — the silence is the story.",
    society:"The watched street changes public behavior — the panopticon dispersed into everyday architecture.",
    technology:"The analog ancestor of networked cameras, facial recognition, and the smart doorbell." },
  causes:["ww2"], effects:["ring"] }
);
